---
import PageLayout from "@/layouts/Base.astro";
---

<PageLayout meta={{ title: "Home" }}>
	<section>
		<h1 class="title mb-12">Welcome!</h1>

		<div class="mb-8 border border-dashed border-gray-400 px-4 py-3 text-sm">
			The competition has not yet launched. Registration, the submission portal, the designated base
			model, and the prize breakdown will be announced on this page when the competition opens
			(expected mid-July 2026).
		</div>

		<p class="mb-4">
			The Steerability Challenge is a NeurIPS 2026 competition on steering large language models:
			making a targeted, deliberate change to a model's behavior while leaving everything else
			intact. Participants design <em>steering policies</em> &mdash; compositions of interventions
			spanning prompting, weight modification (e.g., LoRA adapters), activation steering, and
			decoding-time controls &mdash; that are evaluated against a common base model.
		</p>

		<p class="mb-4">
			This year's target behavior is sycophancy: the tendency of a model to respond with what the
			user appears to want to hear rather than what is accurate. Sycophancy remains a persistent
			failure mode even in state-of-the-art systems and can cause real harm in advisory settings
			(e.g., medicine, law, finance). Your goal is to reduce it as much as possible &mdash; without
			degrading the model's general capabilities.
		</p>

		<p class="mb-4">
			That second clause is the heart of the challenge. Steering a model toward a target behavior is
			well known to cause degradation along other dimensions, and the side-effects of
			<em>composed</em> interventions &mdash; how steering is typically deployed in practice &mdash;
			remain largely unstudied. By scoring submissions on both steering effectiveness and capability
			retention, the competition aims to surface which interventions, and which combinations of
			interventions, control model behavior reliably.
		</p>

		<p class="mb-4">
			All submissions are built with <a
				class="underline hover:no-underline"
				href="https://github.com/IBM/AISteer360"
				target="_blank"
				rel="noreferrer noopener">AI Steerability 360</a
			>, an open-source toolkit that organizes steering methods across four control surfaces (input,
			structural, state, and output) and supports their composition into steering policies. A
			starter kit &mdash; including baseline policies, workbench interfaces for constructing
			steering artifacts, and a local evaluation harness &mdash; will be released ahead of launch.
		</p>

		<div class="mt-6 mb-6 flex items-center gap-2">
			<img src="/competition/darkmode_ais.svg" alt="AI Steerability 360 logo" class="h-10 w-auto" />
			<span>AI Steerability 360</span>
			<div class="text-sm text-gray-400 space-x-3">
				<a
					class="underline hover:no-underline"
					href="https://ibm.github.io/AISteer360/"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noreferrer noopener"
				>
					Docs
				</a>
				<a
					class="underline hover:no-underline"
					href="https://github.com/IBM/AISteer360"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noreferrer noopener"
				>
					Repo
				</a>
				<a
					class="underline hover:no-underline"
					href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.07837"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noreferrer noopener"
				>
					Paper
				</a>
			</div>
		</div>

		<p class="mb-4">
			The competition will be hosted on <a
				class="underline hover:no-underline"
				href="https://www.codabench.org/"
				target="_blank"
				rel="noreferrer noopener">CodaBench</a
			> and will offer both monetary incentives (compute credits and financial awards, subject to sponsorship)
			and non-monetary incentives (co-authorship on the competition summary paper for top-performing
			teams). Questions can be raised on the competition forum, or via the Discord channel and contact
			email announced at launch; bug reports and feature requests for the toolkit go through <a
				class="underline hover:no-underline"
				href="https://github.com/IBM/AISteer360/issues"
				target="_blank"
				rel="noreferrer noopener">GitHub issues</a
			>.
		</p>
